title: Letter from Lillian Casey to Hugh Casey
creator: ['Lillian Casey']
description: Letter from Lillian Casey, aged 20 or 21, to her brother Hugh Casey in Frongoch Internment Camp. Hugh was interned for taking part in the fighting at the GPO during the Easter Rising. His father, James, was a founding member of the Gaelic League.

text: Erster Weltkrieg Первая мировая война Ensimmäinen maailmansota Primeira Guerra Mundial Първа световна война Pirmasis pasaulinis karas Prvi svjetski rat Pirmais pasaules karš Première Guerre mondiale Első világháború Prvá svetová vojna Prva svetovna vojna An Chéad Chogadh Domhanda Primera Guerra Mundial Första världskriget Α΄ Παγκόσμιος Πόλεμος L-Ewwel Gwerra Dinjija World War I Prima guerra mondiale Primera Guerra Mundial Esimene maailmasõda První světová válka Lehen Mundu Gerra I wojna światowa 1. verdenskrig Primul Război Mondial Eerste Wereldoorlog Letter from Lillian Casey to Hugh Casey Letter from Lillian Casey, aged 20 or 21, to her brother Hugh Casey in Frongoch Internment Camp. Hugh was interned for taking part in the fighting at the GPO during the Easter Rising. His father, James, was a founding member of the Gaelic League.

title: Receipt to Irish Transport Workers' Union
creator: ['Hopkins and Hopkins']
description: Hopkins and Hopkins receipt to Irish Transport Workers' Union for the purchase of silver and gold medals.  John J. O'Neill was one of the founding members and a general secretary of the the Irish Transport and General Workers Union. He was one of three trustees to the deeds of Liberty Hall. He lived at 61 Ballybough Road, Dublin and took part in the Rising fighting at both Liberty Hall and the GPO. After the Rising he was interned in Frongoch.
text: Receipt to Irish Transport Workers' Union Hopkins and Hopkins receipt to Irish Transport Workers' Union for the purchase of silver and gold medals.  John J. O'Neill was one of the founding members and a general secretary of the the Irish Transport and General Workers Union. He was one of three trustees to the deeds of Liberty Hall. He lived at 61 Ballybough Road, Dublin and took part in the Rising fighting at both Liberty Hall and the GPO. After the Rising he was interned in Frongoch.

title: ¡El Himno Gallego proscripto por vitando de la radio de La Coruña! estaba invitado a dar una charla ante el micrófono de la Radio coruñesa, sobre un tema gallego. Tuve que negarme ... La Radio coruñesa, siguiendo el ejemplo de las estaciones emisoras de otros países peninsulares, al remate de la jornada de cada día dejaba oir el himno regional y el himno de Riego. Después de varios meses de esta práctica patriótica, el himno regional dejó de oirse ... Porque a los encargados de la Emisora ... se les rogó por personas ... que aquel himno fuese suprimido. Hay quien afirma que también ... se pretendía que el himno de Riego dejara de radiarse, cosa que impidió el gobernador civil al tener noticia de ello ... Hagámos agachar la oreja reaccionaria que con tanta frecuencia se asomó al micrófono de la Radio coruñesa. ¡Esta si que sería obra de verdadero "coruñesismo"!
creator: ['https://hispana.mcu.es/lod/oai:galiciana-bibliotecadegalicia.xunta.es:5071#ent2']
description: Ó fin do texto: (De "El Pueblo Gallego")
concepts: Himnos nacionais Emisoras de radio
